AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; Israel launched an attack on Iran, <i> at the dawn of today, 19 April,&nbsp;</i> hitting a military base in the province of Esfahan, in the central part of the country. Airspace on Tehran and other cities has been closed for a few hours. Explosions were also recorded in southern Syria. Iran declared that it had knocked down several drones and that there was no "no missile attack for now" on the country, after explosions were heard near the central city of Isfahan.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2> Turkey, Israel also affected Syria and Iraq
The attack on Israel this night did not have Iran as the sole objective, but also Syria and Iraq. The news reports are the main Turkish media, including the Cnn Turk, according to which the drones of the Jewish State would have also hit targets with ties with Iran and not yet specified, in Syria and Iraq, two countries where the influence of Tehran has grown in recent years
<h2>Ayeia, no damage nuclear sites Iran, urgency moderation</h2>
The international Atomic Energy Agency Aiea "can confirm that there is no damage to Iran's nuclear sites." This is what we read about the agency's official profile on X. "Director General Rafael Grossi continues to ask everyone for extreme moderation and reiterates that nuclear installations should never be a target in military conflicts. The IAEA is monitoring the situation very carefully", concludes the message
<div </div
<h2>Tajani, we invite caution, no attack on Rafah</h2>
The message that will be launched by Capri, where the G7 of foreign ministers is underway, is an appeal to caution: "The Italian Presidency of the G7 invites to prudence and absolute de-escalation," said Minister Antonio Tajani at Rai News 24 commenting on the Israeli attack of the past hours. "We ask to stop the attack on Rafah, let's see if we're convincing," he added. "Let us make an appeal to de-escalation, to prudence." &nbsp;
<h2>Usa had been warned of the attack
Washington had been warned in advance of the Israeli attack on Iran. Some American media reports it
<h2> Flights from Tehran</h2> airport
According to Iranian state media, Tehran's main airport resumed its regular activity. All flights had been suspended, with the closure of air space, as a result of the attack immediately at the first lights of dawn.&nbsp;
<h2> Australia to its citizens, "leave Israel now"
Australia has asked its citizens to leave Israel immediately. "There is a high threat of terrorist and military attacks against Israel and the interests of Israel in the region - reports a note from the Australian Foreign Department - security conditions could deteriorate rapidly. We ask the Australians who are in Israel or the occupied Palestinian territories to leave if it is possible"
<h2>Media, no damage relevant to attack</h2>
The Iranian official press agency Irna announced that "no significant damage has been reported" following the explosions heard at dawn. "As a result of the activation of air defense in some regions of the country, "no large-scale damage or explosions have been reported," said the agency, based on information from its journalists. The agency added that "the launch of missile defence systems were not received"
<h2> The US: "Never authorized response"
The United States did not give the free way to the Israeli response to Iran. This is reported by the Cnn citing sources of the Biden administration.<br> "We didn't approve the answer," said a government representative. The attack was launched a few hours after Iranian Foreign Minister Hossein Amir-Abdollahian had told Cnn that if Israel had launched attacks there would be a "immediate and high-level" reaction. &nbsp;
<h2>No comment from Israel
The Israeli army "has no comments to make at this moment" but there would be no nuclear facilities among the targets of the attack launched to Iran. The Cnn reported it, which asked for news about the explosions heard in Iran.<br> The targets of attacks, according to a US administration representative, are not nuclear
<h2> Airspace closure
With the closure of airspace over the skies of Iran, according to the flightradar24 site that tracks flights from all over the world, only 24 aircraft that are currently circulating above Iran. The area on the electronic map is the only one that appears semi-empty.
&nbsp;
According to three Iranian officials in the New York Times, the attack would have hit a military air base near the city of Isfahan, central Iran, about 350 km away from the capital Tehran.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

